<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="124" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="124">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="124">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Butaud" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malpighiaceae" genus="Stigmaphyllon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Stigmaphyllon patricianum-firmenichianum" order="Malpighiales" pageId="5" pageNumber="124" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="patricianum-firmenichianum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">Stigmaphyllon patricianum-firmenichianum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the sole member of the genus 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malpighiaceae" genus="Stigmaphyllon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Stigmaphyllon" order="Malpighiales" pageId="5" pageNumber="124" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">Stigmaphyllon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the Loyalty Islands. It is allied with 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malpighiaceae" genus="Stigmaphyllon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Stigmaphyllon discolor" order="Malpighiales" pageId="5" pageNumber="124" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="discolor">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">Stigmaphyllon discolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malpighiaceae" genus="Stigmaphyllon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Stigmaphyllon mcphersonii" order="Malpighiales" pageId="5" pageNumber="124" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mcphersonii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">Stigmaphyllon mcphersonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with which it shares an abaxial tomentose vesture of the blade. Its inclusion under 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malpighiaceae" genus="Stigmaphyllon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Stigmaphyllon taomense" order="Malpighiales" pageId="5" pageNumber="124" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="taomense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">Stigmaphyllon taomense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a species with an abaxially sericeous blade, by 
<bibRefCitation author="Anderson, C" journalOrPublisher="Blumea" pageId="7" pageNumber="126" pagination="73 - 104" publicationUrl="10.3767/000651911X573444" refId="B2" refString="Anderson, C, 2011. Revision of Ryssopterys and transfer to Stigmaphyllon (Malpighiaceae). Blumea 56: 73 - 104, DOI: 10.3767/000651911X573444" title="Revision of Ryssopterys and transfer to Stigmaphyllon (Malpighiaceae)." url="10.3767/000651911X573444" volume="56" year="2011">Anderson (2011)</bibRefCitation>
, may stem from the patchily deciduous vesture of some leaves, which can give the impression of a sericeous blade. Moreover, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Butaud" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malpighiaceae" genus="Stigmaphyllon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Stigmaphyllon patricianum-firmenichianum" order="Malpighiales" pageId="5" pageNumber="124" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="patricianum-firmenichianum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">Stigmaphyllon patricianum-firmenichianum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malpighiaceae" genus="Stigmaphyllon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Stigmaphyllon mcphersonii" order="Malpighiales" pageId="5" pageNumber="124" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mcphersonii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">Stigmaphyllon mcphersonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malpighiaceae" genus="Stigmaphyllon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Stigmaphyllon taomense" order="Malpighiales" pageId="5" pageNumber="124" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="taomense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">Stigmaphyllon taomense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have all 10 stamens, whereas 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malpighiaceae" genus="Stigmaphyllon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Stigmaphyllon discolor" order="Malpighiales" pageId="5" pageNumber="124" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="discolor">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">Stigmaphyllon discolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
bears 12-16 stamens. Nevertheless, its closest affinity in New Caledonia apparently is with 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malpighiaceae" genus="Stigmaphyllon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Stigmaphyllon discolor" order="Malpighiales" pageId="5" pageNumber="124" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="discolor">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">Stigmaphyllon discolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which occurs on most of the southern part of Grande-Terre and Isle of Pines. In South-East Asia and the Western Pacific, it is most similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malpighiaceae" genus="Stigmaphyllon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Stigmaphyllon albidum" order="Malpighiales" pageId="5" pageNumber="124" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="albidum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">Stigmaphyllon albidum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Blume) C.E.Anderson, which can be differentiated by the absence of a style in male flowers. This new species is also clearly different from the widely distributed 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malpighiaceae" genus="Stigmaphyllon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Stigmaphyllon timoriense" order="Malpighiales" pageId="5" pageNumber="124" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="timoriense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="124">Stigmaphyllon timoriense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which has male flowers usually without styles and blades abaxially sericeous to glabrate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
